%========= CHAPTER 1: INTRODUCTION ===========
\chapter{INTRODUCTION}

The AI-Based Postal Sorting System is a software solution developed to modernize and automate the traditional postal sorting processes used in post offices to handle letters, parcels, and small items of logistics. Postal services play an indispensable role in facilitating communication, commerce, and administration across the country by ensuring that postal items are efficiently delivered to their intended destinations. However, the conventional method of sorting these items is highly manual, involving staff reading printed addresses, identifying PIN codes, and placing items into their respective bins or dispatch zones. While this process has supported postal operations effectively for decades, it remains labour-intensive, time-consuming, and prone to human errors, particularly during peak operational hours when thousands of items need to be processed quickly.

With recent technological advancements, industries are increasingly adopting Artificial Intelligence (AI) and automation to enhance their operational workflows. Postal systems are no exception, as they require timely delivery and high accuracy to maintain public trust and operational efficiency. The AI-Based Postal Sorting System utilizes Optical Character Recognition (OCR) technology to extract printed address data and combines it with automated sorting logic to categorize items based on their PIN codes. This eliminates the dependency on manual sorting and reduces the possibility of errors while significantly improving the sorting speed. Furthermore, the system provides a web-based platform with an intuitive user interface for postal staff to capture images of letters and parcels, process them, and view sorting results instantly. The integration of an admin dashboard allows tracking and management of all processed items, ensuring transparency, accountability, and operational monitoring within the postal hub. Thus, this project demonstrates the practical application of AI, OCR, and Web technologies to efficiently solve real-world postal sorting challenges.

\section{General Background}
The Indian postal network is one of the largest in the world, handling millions of letters, documents, and parcels every day across diverse geographic regions. The classification of these postal items is a crucial function performed in branch offices, head post offices, and central distribution hubs to ensure accurate and timely delivery. Traditionally, this process involves staff reading each address label, identifying its destination PIN code, and manually placing it into bins designated for specific regions or delivery zones. The Postal Index Number (PIN) system in India was introduced to simplify and systematise mail sorting and delivery. It is a six-digit code where each digit signifies a hierarchical regional categorisation, helping sort items efficiently from national to local levels.

However, the increasing population, urbanisation, and rapid growth of e-commerce have resulted in exponential growth in postal volumes, creating significant challenges for manual sorting processes. Manual sorting leads to longer processing times, increased fatigue among staff, and a higher chance of misplacement or dispatch errors, especially when dealing with high item volumes daily. Developed countries have addressed this challenge by deploying conveyor-based sorting systems integrated with barcode scanners and AI-based address recognition to automate sorting operations at large postal hubs. However, such infrastructure requires substantial capital investment and technical integration, making it less feasible for regional and rural post offices with budget constraints.

In this context, a software-based AI postal sorting system using OCR technology provides a practical, scalable, and cost-effective solution to enhance postal operations. The proposed system uses Easy OCR, an open-source optical character recognition engine, to extract address data from captured images of letters and parcels. It then applies regex parsing logic to identify the valid PIN code from the extracted text and maps it to predefined virtual bins or dispatch zones using automated sorting logic. The system further includes tracking and administrative dashboard modules to maintain processing records, monitor operations, and a accountability. This approach not only bridges the gap between manual and fully robotic sorting but also prepares the postal system for future integration with physical automation technologies while enabling students to demonstrate AI applications effectively in real-world service sectors.

\section{Objective}
The main objective of the AI-Based Postal Sorting System project is to develop a robust software application that automates the extraction of printed addresses and PIN codes from postal item images and classifies these items into their respective bins or dispatch zones using AI-based sorting logic. The project aims to design a web-based platform with a user-friendly interface for postal staff to capture real-time images using webcams or upload stored images of letters and parcels for processing. The integrated OCR module extracts the printed address text from these images with high accuracy, while the parsing module identifies the valid six-digit PIN code essential for sorting. The sorting logic module then maps the extracted PIN code to its designated bin or delivery zone based on predefined mapping tables. Furthermore, the system includes a sorting animation module that visually demonstrates the movement of the item into its assigned bin on the screen, emulating an automated sorting conveyor system for effective demonstration. In addition, the system maintains a comprehensive database record of each sorted item, including details such as extracted address, PIN code, assigned bin, date, and processing time. The admin dashboard module enables administrators to monitor and manage these records, view sorting history, and generate reports for operational analysis. Overall, the project seeks to improve the efficiency, accuracy, and management of postal sorting workflows while demonstrating the integration of AI, computer vision, and web technologies in a practical and innovative manner suitable for academic learning and future industrial implementation.

