\chapter{LITERATURE SURVEY}

Postal services globally are undergoing rapid transformation through the integration of Artificial Intelligence (AI) and computer vision technologies to enhance efficiency, accuracy, and reliability in sorting workflows. Velu and Vivekanandan (2010) \cite{velu2010}, in their study Automatic Letter Sorting for Indian Postal Address Recognition System Based on PIN Codes, proposed a postal address recognition and automated sorting system tailored for Indian postal operations. Their approach utilised Connected Component (CC) labelling to segment handwritten numerals on envelopes, followed by classification using Artificial Neural Networks (ANN). To automate physical sorting, they designed barcodes corresponding to PIN codes to be printed on envelopes, enabling barcode scanners and conveyor belt mechanisms with electronic gates to direct letters into designated bins. The system achieved 99.5\% sorting accuracy, demonstrating the feasibility of implementing such automated solutions in large postal hubs. However, the authors acknowledged challenges in scaling this infrastructure to all regional post offices due to the required capital investment and maintenance.

Similarly, Pavithra et al. (2020) \cite{pavithra2020}, in their International Journal of Computer Applications publication titled Recognition of Handwritten and Printed Text using Tesseract OCR Engine, examined the effectiveness of Tesseract OCR for printed and handwritten text recognition. The authors highlighted that Tesseract’s LSTM-based neural network models provide high accuracy for printed text extraction but face limitations with handwritten text unless trained extensively on diverse datasets. Their research emphasised the importance of preprocessing techniques such as grayscale-conversion, binarization, and noise reduction to enhance input image quality and recognition performance. They also recommended integrating Tesseract with image processing libraries like OpenCV to improve results, especially in document digitisation, form processing, and postal address extraction applications.

In a related study, Jadhav et al. (2019) \cite{jadhav2019}, published in IRJET, explored the use of machine vision-based automation for postal sorting. Their system employed cameras to capture parcel images and applied OCR techniques to extract destination addresses and other relevant information. The processed data enabled robotic manipulators to sort parcels into appropriate bins, thereby increasing operational efficiency and reducing human errors commonly associated with manual sorting methods. The authors concluded that machine vision-based postal automation aligns with global trends in logistics but noted infrastructural and financial limitations in implementing conveyor-based robotic systems in smaller postal branches, suggesting software simulation as a viable academic and prototype approach.

In a more advanced study, Li et al. (2021) \cite{li2021}, in their IEEE Access paper titled AI-Based Parcel Sorting Using Deep Learning, proposed a robotic sorting framework using multi-task deep learning models to handle cluttered and disorderly stacked parcels efficiently. Their system included a lightweight object detection network optimised through channel-level pruning and dynamic weighting strategies to balance detection speed and accuracy while maintaining a smaller model size. Furthermore, the pose estimation network integrated key point detection to determine optimal grasping positions for robotic arms. Experimental results showed a sorting success rate of 89.7\%, indicating the potential of deep learning in achieving precise and rapid automated parcel sorting in complex logistics environments.

Additionally, Obagbuwa and Mogorosi (2023) \cite{obagbuwa2023}, in their chapter Modeling and Simulation of a Robot Arm with Conveyor Belt Using MATLAB Simulink Model, demonstrated a detailed simulation of a five-degree-of-freedom robotic arm integrated with two conveyor belts for pick-and-place operations. Using MATLAB Simulink and Simscape Multibody, they optimised actuator torque, motor requirements, and mechanical configurations, showcasing how robotic arm modelling and simulation can enhance industrial automation workflows. Their study emphasised the importance of simulation before physical deployment to ensure efficiency, cost-effectiveness, and safety in automation projects.

From the literature reviewed, it is evident that while industrial postal automation leverages robotics, barcodes, and deep learning for high-speed and accurate sorting, software-based OCR and AI sorting systems provide a practical and scalable solution for postal services. These studies demonstrate how integrating AI technologies such as Tesseract OCR, neural networks, object detection models, and simulation frameworks with automated sorting logic can significantly improve operational efficiency and accuracy, paving the way towards fully automated postal and logistics hubs in the future.

