\chapter{SYSTEM ANALYSIS}

\section{Existing System}
The existing postal sorting system predominantly relies on manual operations involving human personnel who inspect, interpret, and sort physical mail based on the destination address or pin code written on parcels and envelopes. This method, although functional, is significantly time-consuming, labor-intensive, and error-prone, particularly in high-volume postal centers or logistics hubs handling thousands of items daily.
In the conventional setup, staff members visually examine each parcel to read the recipient’s address and manually determine the appropriate bin or route for sorting. This process demands constant concentration and accuracy and becomes increasingly inefficient when dealing with poor handwriting, worn-out labels, or damaged packages. Any delay or mistake in reading and interpreting the pin code can result in misrouting, delivery delays, or even lost parcels, affecting customer satisfaction and operational trust.
Furthermore, this traditional system lacks any form of automation, centralized data storage, or tracking logs, making it difficult to monitor performance metrics, trace past sorting actions, or analyze error patterns. Supervisors are unable to audit the sorting process effectively, as there is no digital record of who handled a parcel, when it was sorted, or where it was directed. This lack of transparency and accountability can lead to inefficiencies, especially in larger networks.
Another significant limitation is the absence of real-time feedback or error detection mechanisms. If a mistake occurs—such as assigning a parcel to the wrong bin—there is no system to catch or rectify the error immediately. Additionally, staff training in such systems is largely informal and does not leverage digital simulation or visualization, making it harder for new employees to learn or understand operational flow efficiently.
In terms of reporting, the current system generally depends on manual documentation, paper-based records, or isolated spreadsheets maintained by individual operators. This approach makes it difficult to consolidate data, identify trends, or generate reliable performance summaries for management review.
Despite some organizations attempting minor digital enhancements—like barcode-based sorting or camera-assisted tracking—many postal offices and small courier services still use this outdated manual model due to budget constraints, lack of infrastructure, or technical know-how. Consequently, these systems struggle to meet modern demands for speed, traceability, and accuracy in mail processing.

\section{Proposed System}
The proposed system aims to modernize and automate the process of postal sorting by leveraging advanced technologies such as Optical Character Recognition (OCR), machine learning logic, and real-time data visualization. Traditional postal sorting methods rely heavily on manual labor, making the process time-consuming, error-prone, and inefficient. The developed solution introduces a fully automated pipeline that captures parcel images, extracts address and pin code information using OCR, and sorts items into their respective destination bins based on pin code mappings. This automation significantly enhances sorting accuracy, saves time, and reduces human errors. The system is particularly beneficial for logistics centers and postal departments seeking to improve operational efficiency. By integrating image acquisition, preprocessing, and pin code extraction, the solution ensures faster processing, improved reliability, and greater operational performance.

The AI-based postal sorting system is designed with a role-based access control mechanism that distinguishes between two types of users: Admin and Postal Staff, each with clearly defined responsibilities and interfaces. The Admin plays a supervisory role and is primarily responsible for managing user accounts. This includes adding new staff members, editing existing user details.Admins can create bin globally accessed by all staffs. Admins can also view the complete sorting history generated by the postal staff and monitor login activities for administrative oversight. This role ensures controlled access and accountability within the system, maintaining operational security and structured user management.

On the other hand, the Postal Staff interact with the system to carry out the actual sorting process. They can capture images of letters and parcels in real-time using a webcam. Once captured, the system automatically processes the image and displays the extracted address and pin code using OCR. The staff can then view the extracted details, which are presented in a clean and readable format for verification. A key highlight of the project is the animated visualization that shows the parcel moving towards its designated bin on the screen based on the pin code logic. This real-time feedback not only confirms successful sorting but also enhances user interactivity and system engagement. In addition, Postal Staff can view the contents of each bin, export sorting reports in PDF format, and review previously sorted items through the sorted history section. This structured workflow empowers staff to manage parcel sorting efficiently while ensuring transparency and traceability across all stages of the process.

The core functionality of the system is driven by the integration of Optical Character Recognition (OCR), specifically using the Easy OCR engine, which is capable of recognizing both printed and handwritten text with high accuracy. To ensure reliable extraction of address and pin code information, the system performs a series of image preprocessing steps such as grayscale conversion, binarization, thresholding, and noise removal. These processes enhance the clarity and contrast of the text regions, preparing the image for more accurate OCR processing. After extracting the complete address, the system applies pattern recognition logic to isolate and validate the pin code, ensuring accurate identification regardless of its position or format within the text. One of the standout features of the system is the real-time animation-based sorting, which visually simulates the movement of a parcel toward its respective bin based on the extracted pin code. This dynamic visualization not only provides immediate confirmation of successful sorting but also enhances the overall user experience, making the process interactive, transparent, and easy to understand. The combined use of OCR for intelligent data extraction and animated feedback for visual tracking forms the foundation of the system’s smart and automated postal sorting capabilities.

