\section{Methodology}
The development of the Postal Sorting Automation System follows the Agile methodology, an iterative approach that allows for continuous refinement and adaptation based on user feedback and evolving requirements. Agile enables the project to be divided into smaller, manageable sprints, each including planning, development, testing, and review phases. This ensures rapid identification and resolution of issues, particularly useful for systems relying on OCR, PIN parsing, and image preprocessing.

Agile promotes close collaboration between developers, testers, and end-users such as postal staff and administrators. Their ongoing input ensures that system features—like sorting logic, animation visualization, and error handling—are aligned with practical postal operations. Continuous integration and testing throughout each sprint help maintain system reliability and functionality.

The methodology also supports progressive implementation, where modules such as address extraction, bin assignment, and report generation are developed and improved incrementally. By embracing Agile, the system remains flexible and adaptable to changes, while ensuring timely delivery of features that improve sorting accuracy and operational efficiency.

In essence, Agile fosters a user-centered, collaborative environment that ensures the system is responsive, efficient, and well-suited to the real-world dynamics of automated postal sorting.

